Target a subsidy

Anran Zheng

2021/11/03

Introduction

Most organizations are client-based. The government and enterprises work on behalf of houseowners. For example, the promise of Department of Housing and Community Development (HCD) is to attract eligible homeowners who can enroll the home repair tax credit program, but only 11% of eligible homeowners can take the credit. Due to potential risks as well as opportunites, most homeowners choose not to take the credit.To reach the goal of HCD, a decision-making model should be built and cost/benefit analysis should then be conducted. This study focused on the governmental resource allocation for company based on the client-level data and conducted the resulting intelligence for cost/benefit analysis. The decision of not taking credit can be predicted, which can guide HCD how to allocate their limited outreach resources more effectively.

Data exploration

In this study, 19 potential variables associations with the likelihood of taking the credit were chosen, and Figure 1 visualized 7 continuous features of them. It is clear that most features are almost the same between whether houseowners take the credit or not, except inflation_rate, previous (# of contacts before this campaign for this ind) and unemploy_rate. The higher the inflation rate is, the less likely that a client will take the credit, and the more contacts before this campaign for this individual, the more possible that a client will take the credit. Notice that the unemployment rate was negative value for no credit taken, this study will ignore unemployment rate in our further model. Figure 2 shows how these numeric variables vary in the continuous scale, Only the varying trend of age is basically the same between whether the clients will take the credits.

Feature engineering

The Sensitivity (True Positive Rate) for a model with all the features is very low. In order to increase the sensitivity, some new features should be engineered. Based on the curve lines in Figure 2, we classified all the numeric variables into different categories. Different seasons are also classified from the month variable. The differences between each range should be significant. We also tried to classify other categorical variables, such as campaign, jobs and education. These variables are also proven to be effective in improving the sensitivity in later analysis.

housing.eng<-housing%>%
  mutate(
    age.cat=case_when(age < 30 ~ "age_30",
                      age >= 30 & age < 50 ~ "age30_50",
                      age >= 50 & age < 65 ~ "age50_65",
                      age >= 65 ~ "age65+"),
    previous.cat = case_when(
      previous == 0 ~ "previous0",
      previous > 0 ~ "previousNOT0"),
    conf.cat = case_when(
      cons.conf.idx < -50 ~ "conf_50-",
      cons.conf.idx >= -50 & cons.conf.idx < -45 ~ "conf-50_-45",
      cons.conf.idx >= -45 & cons.conf.idx < -40 ~ "conf-45_-40",
      cons.conf.idx >= -40 & cons.conf.idx < -35 ~ "conf-40_-35",
      cons.conf.idx >= -35 & cons.conf.idx < -30 ~ "conf-35_-30",
      cons.conf.idx >= -30 & cons.conf.idx < -25 ~ "conf-30_-25"),
    price.cat=case_when(
      cons.price.idx < 93 ~ "price93-",
      cons.price.idx >= 93 & cons.price.idx < 93.5 ~ "price93_93.5",
      cons.price.idx >= 93.5 & cons.price.idx < 94 ~ "price93.5_94",
      cons.price.idx >= 94 & cons.price.idx < 94.5 ~ "price94_94.5",
      cons.price.idx >= 94.5 ~ "price94.5+"),
    inflation.cat = case_when(
      inflation_rate >= 0.5 & inflation_rate < 1.5 ~ "inflation0.5_1.5",
      inflation_rate >= 1.5 & inflation_rate < 2.5 ~ "inflation1.5_2.5",
      inflation_rate >= 2.5 & inflation_rate < 3.5 ~ "inflation2.5_3.5",
      inflation_rate >= 3.5 & inflation_rate < 4.5 ~ "inflation3.5_4.5",
      inflation_rate >= 4.5 ~ "inflation4.5+"),
    repair.cat=case_when(
      spent_on_repairs < 5000 ~ "repair5000-",
      spent_on_repairs >= 5000 & spent_on_repairs < 5100 ~ "repair5000_5100",
      spent_on_repairs >= 5100 & spent_on_repairs < 5200 ~ "repair5100_5200",
      spent_on_repairs >= 5200 ~ "repair5200+"),
    season = case_when(
      month == "mar"| month == "apr"| month == "may" ~ "Spring",
      month == "jun" | month == "jul" | month == "aug"~ "Summer",
      month == "sep"| month == "oct" | month == "nov" ~ "Fall",
      month == "dec" ~ "Winter"),
    education.cat = case_when(
      education == "basic.4y" | education == "basic.6y" | education == "basic.9y" ~ "Basic",
      education == "high.school" ~ "HighSchool",
      education == "professional.course" ~ "Professional",
      education == "university.degree" ~ "University",
      education == "illiterate" ~ "Illiterate",
      education == "unknown" ~ "Unknown"),
    job.cat = ifelse(job == "self-employed"|job =="unemloyed", "Self_or_unemployed", 
                     "Other"),
    campaign.cat = case_when(
      campaign >= 0 & campaign < 2  ~ "Once",
      campaign >= 2 & campaign < 10  ~ "2 to 9 times",
      campaign > 9                    ~ "More than 9 times")
  )

Figure 6 shows those new engineered features with the likelihood of taking the credit. The gap between whether taking credits or not is still large, though decreasing slightly. Generally, those houseowners are more likely to take the credits: houseowners aged from 30 to 50, houseowners whose consumer confidence index ranges from -35 to -45, houseowners whose US inflation rate is 0.5 to 1.5, houseowners whose price index is below 93, houseowners who spent 5000 to 5100 dollars on home repairs, houseowners whose number of contacts is less than nine for this campaign, houseowners whose education attainment is university, and houseowners who are contacted in summer. To further test the most significant variables affecting the decision of houseowners, the Logistic regression model will be applied in the following analysis.

Logistic regression

Training/Testing sets

In order to conduct the Logistic regression model for estimation, first of all, the dataset is split into a 65/35 training/test set. Then based on the training/test set, two logistic regression models were built. One is called the kitchen sink regression, which selects all the original, untransformed variables. It consists of both numeric and categorical variables; the other is called as the engineered regression, which picks some engineering features and orginal categorical variables. Keeping in mind that the sensitivity should be improved as possible, we went through several trials, changed the variables in this model and finally, include the following variables in the engineered regression model: age.cat, previous.cat, price.cat, conf.cat, inflation.cat, job.cat, marital, education.cat,taxLien, mortgage, taxbill_in_phl, contact, day_of_week, campaign, pdays, season, poutcome,campaign.cat. Both the kitchen sink and engineered models dataset is also split into test and training set.

#Split your data into a 65/35 training/test set.
set.seed(3456)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(housing.eng$y,
                                  y=paste(
                                    housing.eng$education,
                                    housing.eng$taxLien
                                          ),
                                  p = .65,
                                  list = FALSE,
                                  times = 1)
housingTrain <- housing.eng[ trainIndex,]
housingTest  <- housing.eng[-trainIndex,]

#kitchen sink
kitchenTrain<-housingTrain%>%
  dplyr::select(y,y_numeric,age, previous, unemploy_rate, 
                cons.price.idx, cons.conf.idx, inflation_rate, spent_on_repairs,
                job, marital, education,taxLien,
                mortgage, taxbill_in_phl, contact, month,
                day_of_week, campaign, pdays, poutcome)

kitchenTest<-housingTest%>%
  dplyr::select(y,y_numeric,age, previous, unemploy_rate, 
                cons.price.idx, cons.conf.idx, inflation_rate, spent_on_repairs,
                job, marital, education,taxLien,
                mortgage, taxbill_in_phl, contact, month,
                day_of_week, campaign, pdays, poutcome)

#engineering
engTrain<-housingTrain%>%
  dplyr::select(
    y,y_numeric,age.cat, previous.cat, price.cat, conf.cat, inflation.cat, 
    job.cat, marital, education.cat,taxLien,
    mortgage, taxbill_in_phl, contact, 
    day_of_week, campaign, pdays, season, poutcome,campaign.cat
  )

engTest<-housingTest%>%
  dplyr::select(
    y,y_numeric,age.cat, previous.cat, price.cat, conf.cat, inflation.cat, 
    job.cat, marital, education.cat,taxLien,
    mortgage, taxbill_in_phl, contact, 
    day_of_week, campaign, pdays, season, poutcome,campaign.cat
  )

Regression summary

The kitchen sink regression summary is as follows. Most factors are not significant, except age, unemployment_rate, cons.price.idx, cons.conf.idx, contacttelephone, monthmar and day_of_weekwed. Those variables, except unemployment_rate due to its existing negative values, will be involved in the engineer model. The AIC is 1542.9 and our goal is to decrease this as possible, meanwhile, adding more significant factors so that the sensitivity can be improved.

#kitchen sink regression
kitchen.reg<-glm(y_numeric ~ .,
                 data=kitchenTrain%>% 
                   dplyr::select(-y),
                 family="binomial" (link="logit"))
summary(kitchen.reg)

Confusion matrix

To further compare these two regression models, confusion Matrix is created which shows the number of reference, the comparison between observed and predicted given the 50% threshold. There were 1258 true negatives, 428 false positives, 275 false negatives and 506 true positives. The accuracy, sensitivity and specificity just improve a little from kitchen sink regression to engineer regression, which suggests that engineer regression is slightly better than predicting people not taking the credits. For engineer regression, the accuracy (90.78%) and the Specificity(98.28%) is high. The specificity, also known as true positive rate, means that 98.28% of actual positives that were predicted to be positive. The Sensitivity (27.15%) is low, improving by 5% compared with the kitchen sink regression, and it means that 27.15% of actual negatives that were predicted to be negatives, which also known as true negative rate.

ROC curve

The Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve is a typical indicator of goodness of fit, which is plotted for both model in figure 7 and 8, where x-axis denotes the false positive fraction while y-axis denotes the true positive fraction. The trends of both ROC lines are similar: when false positive fraction is less than 0.1, true positive fractions increased sharply as the false positive fraction increased. When false positive fraction is greater than 0.1, the increment of true positive fraction turn to become smoother. The grey line represents the perfect fit line, which reflects that both the models are overfit. The Area Under the Curve metric is also calculated: for kitchen sink it is 0.7531, while engineer model is 0.7588, which slightly increased.

Despite the engineer model does not differ much from the kitchen sink model, we still choose the engineer model for its better performance (higher accuracy, sensitivity and specificity) and based on that, conduct cost benefit analysis.

Cost and benefits

Cost: HCD is willing to allocate $2850 per homeowner who is predicted to take the credit. The credit also costs $5,000 per homeowner which can be used toward home improvement.
Benefits: After taking the credit, the houses can be sold with a $10,000 premium, on average.
The cost/benefit equations for each confusion metric are listed as follows:
- True Positive : Predicted correctly homeowner would take the credit; allocated the marketing resources, and 25% took the credit, while 75% didnt.
True Positive = ((10000-2850-5000) * (Count * 25%)) + (-2850 * (Count * 75%))
- True Negative : Predicted correctly homeowner would not take the credit, no marketing resources were allocated, and no credit was allocated.
True Negative = 0
- False Positive: Predicted incorrectly homeowner would take the credit; allocated marketing resources; no credit allocated.
False Positive = -2850 * Count
- False Negative: We predicted that a homeowner would not take the credit but they did. These are likely homeowners who signed up for reasons unrelated to the marketing campaign. Thus, we 0 out this category, assuming the cost/benefit of this is $0.
False Negative = (10000-5000) * Count
The table of cost and benefits is shown as table 1, with a threshold of 0.5. which means that the model will recognize as people who are willing to take the credits if the predicted likelihood is greater than 50%.

#cost_benefit_table
cost_benefit_table <-
  eng.testProbs %>%
  count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
  summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
            True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
            False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
            False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
  gather(Variable, Count) %>%
  mutate(Revenue =
           case_when(Variable == "True_Negative"  ~ 0,
                     Variable == "True_Positive"  ~ ((10000-2850-5000) * (Count * .25)) + 
                       (-2850 * (Count * .75)),
                     Variable == "False_Negative" ~ (10000-5000) * Count,
                     Variable == "False_Positive" ~ -2850 * Count)) %>%
  bind_cols(data.frame(Description = c(
    "We predicted no allocation and homeowner did not take credit",
    "We predicted allocation and homeowner took credit",
    "We predicted no allocation and homeowner took credit",
    "We predicted allocation and the homeowner did not take credit")))

kable(cost_benefit_table,
      caption = "Table 1. Cost/Benefit Table") %>% 
  kable_styling()

Figure 11 plots the the confusion metric outcomes for each Threshold, a plot of trade-offs. False negative revenue is the only kind of revenue that has positive value. As the threshold goes up, the model predicted incorrectly that more homeowner would take the credit, with no resource or credit allocated and more revenue generated. The False positive revenue remained 0 all the time, while the number of homeowners not taking the credits goes up. At higher threshold, the model assumes that no homeowner would take the credit and no revenue is lost to false negatives. A low threshold assumes that few houseownwers are predicted to take the credits, but at higher threshold, the revenue is close to 0.

#Plot the confusion metric outcomes for each Threshold
iterateThresholds <- function(data) {
  x = .01
  all_prediction <- data.frame()
  while (x <= 1) {
    
    this_prediction <-
      eng.testProbs %>%
      mutate(predOutcome = ifelse(Probs > x, 1, 0)) %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
      gather(Variable, Count) %>%
      mutate(Revenue =
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Negative", 0,
                      ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive",((10000-2850-5000) * (Count * .25)) + 
                               (-2850 * (Count * .75)),
                             ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", (10000-5000) * Count,
                                    ifelse(Variable == "False_Positive", -2850 * Count, 0)))),
             Threshold = x)
    
    all_prediction <- rbind(all_prediction, this_prediction)
    x <- x + .01
  }
  return(all_prediction)
}

whichThreshold <- iterateThresholds(eng.testProbs)

whichThreshold %>%
  ggplot(.,aes(Threshold, Revenue, colour = Variable)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_colour_manual(values = palette5[c(5, 1:3)]) +    
  labs(title = "Figure 11. Revenue by confusion matrix type and threshold",
       y = "Revenue") +
  guides(colour=guide_legend(title = "Confusion Matrix"))

Optimizing the cost/benefit relationship

Figure 12 and figure 13 show how Threshold as a function of Total_Revenue and Total_Count_of_Credits. As the threshold increases, the total counts of credits as well as revenue increase. At larger threshold, the revenue tends to become more stable. The vertical line denotes the optimal threshold, which is about 0.88, which means that when the likelihood that houseowners will take the credit is 88%, with about 150 amounts of credits. Probably due to the influence of false negatives, the threshold is larger than we imagine, because the model considered more homeowners will not take the credits but they did, which leads to the waste of resource allocation.

whichThreshold_revenue <- 
  whichThreshold %>% 
  mutate(allocations = ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive", (Count * 0.25),
                             ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", Count, 0))) %>% 
  group_by(Threshold) %>% 
  summarize(Total_Revenue = sum(Revenue),
            Total_Count_of_Credits = sum(allocations))

Conclusion

Our goal is targeting home owners who qualify for a home tax credit program, in detail, helping HCD maximize revenues by avoiding the waste of resource allocation. Two models, the kitchen sink and the engineering, were created to predict house owners who will take the credits, and both were compared based on several indicators of goodness of fit. The engineering model perform slightly better, however, this model shouldnt be put into production for three reasons. First, according to the confusion matrix, this model improves slightly. The sensitivity is still small (around 27%), which suggest that only a small proportion of actual negatives that were predicted to be negatives. This might be misleading to HCD, since HCD should take some measurements to urge people taking the credits rather than incorrectly judge that their willingness to take the credits. Secondly, the optimal threshold predicted by this model is 0.88, suggesting that house owners will be reach out to take the credits when the possibility is greater or equal than 88%. This seems confusing because we expect that the threshold should be lower so that HCD can reach out more house owners to take the credit. Finally, despite this model can help improve cost and benefits, fairness is not judged in this study. Across-group generlizability should be considered to enhance the usefulness of the model.
Looking at the original housing Subsidy datasets, notably there are much more records of not taking the credits than taking the credits. But our goal is to predict house owners who can take the credits. The few records on taking the credits will cause some bias. Therefore, in order to make the model better, data with more even distribution of whether taking the credits or not should be considered. Moreover, it is important to understand the motivation for house owner who takes the credit. These targeting groups should be surveyed in many aspects, such as their economic levels and family components. More potential factors should also be considered in understanding the motivation of willingness to take the credits.
Finally, keep in mind that prediction models should not be relied too much. It can only set as a reference to the government. Even with a more accurate prediction model, HDC should still figure out some useful and rational strategies to attract more house owners take the credits, at the same time, consider the limited amount of resource allocation.
